The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 London, July 26: Infrastructure firm GMR has emerged as a surprise bidder in the 300-million auction for the UKs biggest coal-fired power station, EDF Energys Eggborough unit in North Yorkshire, The Sunday Times reported. GMR founder G. M. Rao has begun sounding out city bankers to line up financing for the bid, the newspaper said.                             
	 London, July 26: The high rainfall deficit in June implies a fall in kharif crop production during 2009-10, the Centre for Monitoring Indian Economy said in its monthly report. The crop production will fall 4.7 per cent during the year after recording a marginal increase of 0.3 per cent in 2008-09.                             
	 New Delhi, July 26: The steel ministry will soon send a proposal to the cabinet on Rashtriya Ispat Nigam Ltds plans of acquiring majority stakes in five companies, of which three are mining entities. The five ailing state-run companies are Orissa Mineral Development Corporation, Bisra Stone Lime Co, Karanpura Development Co, Scott amp; Saxyby and Eastern Investments Ltd.                             
	 Toronto, July 26: Ericsson will acquire a major part of Nortels North American wireless business for $1.13 billion. The Swedish firm was the successful bidder for the bankrupt Canadian companys CDMA and LTE technologies. The purchase is structured as an asset sale at a purchase price of $1.13 billion on a cash and debt free basis.                             
	 Mumbai, July 26: The countrys largest lender, the State Bank of India, has told the government that it would earn a minimum profit of Rs 11,000 crore in the current fiscal, 21 per cent more that what it achieved in the previous fiscal.                            
	 New Delhi, July 26: Money received by an employee of a foreign company while leaving the firm, even if it is paid as non-compete fee, will be taxable in India, according to a Delhi bench of the Income Tax Appellate Tribunal.                             
	 New Delhi, July 26: The country may face a huge shortage of onion before the onset of winter because of the late monsoon. This could spike onion prices.                                                                                                                           
